<div class="indented"><a id="comment-1935"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/switching-popular-vote-electoral-college#comment-1935" class="active">Sovereign</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Wed, 2006-07-26 23:57.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>I guess it depends on the view of people as to how independent states are.  They submit to federalism, this would be one other way.</p>

<p>There could well be a 14th amendment challenge to such a compact.  The 14th does demand that every male citizen over 21 gets to vote in any election of the electors of the President, but it doesn&#8217;t say that it&#8217;s that state&#8217;s electors.  But it will be argued.   The state constitution and statute may have things to say about these matters, I don&#8217;t think a compact can supersede a state constitution.   </p>
</div>
